  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Viewing the Moon on the Fifteenth Day of the Fifth Month
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, I lament that I came late to the Way.
    Instead, I fell prey to the deceptions of ghosts and demons.
    Vast and desolate, after the people have departed,
    The eternal moon hangs full in its season.
    The mirror-case retains only the traces of empty hands,
    And perhaps there lingers some promise in the underworld.
    I cannot bear to see its reflection on the pond—
    Two streams of tears drip upon the dew-laden leaves.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Way' (道) refers to the Buddhist or Daoist path of enlightenment that the speaker regrets not pursuing earnestly enough.
  - key: ''
    value: The mirror imagery suggests both vanity and the fleeting nature of earthly concerns, contrasted with the eternal celestial bodies.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'underworld' (泉臺) is a classical Chinese reference to the realm of the afterlife, suggesting the speaker's contemplation of mortality.
